I"'	<h3 id="cscb07-dollar-store">CSCB07 Dollar Store</h3>
<p>The “Dollar Store” was a android sales application created in my second year in a software design course.</p>

<p>The task was to create an online shopping center featuring various items such as fishing poles, umbrellas, socks and a bunch of other items.  I worked in an amazing group with 3 of my classmates, many of us beginners to real software development.  We quickly learned how to design good code, how to implement standard software development practices and methodologies, and how to work as a team.</p>

<h3 id="technicalities">Technicalities</h3>
<p>The application featured 3 different roles, a Customer, Employee and Admin.  This was the first Android application that I had created, and I am thankful to have had such a great team to develop it with.  We climbed the learning curve for Android Studio, as well as</p>

<p>The customer could create an account and “shop” with the limited inventory.  Once an account was created, the customer had the option to load a shopping cart from a previous shopping session, or create a new on entirely.</p>

<p>The Employee had responsibilities of selling items to the customer and managing the inventory.  The Employee could view a log of recently purchased items and restock/order more items for the inventory.</p>

<p>The Admin had the most power of all.  The admin could perform all employee level tasks as well as export the current items in the database.</p>

<h3 id="our-journey-using-agile">Our Journey Using Agile</h3>
<p>In an attempt to balance the project workload with our other courses, we held tri-weekly scrum meetings where we updated each other on what was completed in the last sprint, as well as bringing up any obstacles that were in the way of us completing our tasks.  We also held sprint planning for each phase of the project where hashed out the details of what we wanted to complete and by when.</p>

<p>Within each sprint planning, we voted as a team to assign story points per feature, then based on each team member’s skillset (and level of enthusiasm) we held a resource allocation meeting to figure out who was going to work on what.</p>

<p>Why we called it the “Dollar Store” was because, just like the real Dollar Store, almost everything in the store was way more than a dollar.</p>
